    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks. i think it might be a nutrient thing though because the yellowing is really concentrated on the older leaves specifically. i've heard something about soil pH affecting how they take up food? how do i check that and what should i aim for?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "You are correct; soil pH can absolutely impact nutrient uptake, and older leaves are often the first to show signs of this. You can check your soil pH by purchasing a simple home testing kit from a garden center. For tomatoes, you generally want a slightly acidic to neutral range, ideally between 6.0 and 6.8. If your pH is too high or too low, you can adjust it using lime (to raise pH) or sulfur (to lower pH).",
      "source": "target",
